<div id="outline-container-orgaa0da20" class="outline-2">
<h2 id="orgaa0da20">Mail re:Boosted Limits</h2>
<div class="outline-text-2" id="text-orgaa0da20">
<p>
HI Stephane,
</p>

<p>
I agree this is definentely a point of confusion. Based on the
presentations from the boosted teams I think the main issue in scaling
is that Boosted analysis has significant statistical uncertianty on
the expected 95% CL, coming from a non-trivial statistical uncertianty
on the expected background prediction. (In the resolved analysis, the
statistical on uncertianty on the expected background is much
smaller.)
</p>

<p>
This effect is not currently captured in the Brazilian bands we use to
report the expected limits. The yellow and green colored bands reflect
the level uncertianty we expect on observed limits (eg: including both
the statistical uncertianty on the background AND on expected SR data
yeild). We dont separate out the statistical component on the expected
limits, and simply quote the point estimate for the 95% CL.
</p>

<p>
We could potentially convey this with a modified version A (cartoon)
of how we might show both pieces would something ilke:
